Technology Trends Who will win the online wallet war?
The electronic money revolution is coming. Bitcoin is the major player, but its rivals want your digital cash too, says tech trend expert Dan Smith. Paying fair: digital currency such as Bitcoin and Litecoin may signal the end of using credit cards to pay online Photo: (c) Cavan Images	By Dan SmithWired technology writer
5:44PM BST 16 Aug 2013
Read more on the latest tech trends >>
Once you’ve ordered a pint at the Pembury Tavern you have to make a further choice: which currency to pay with? For this pub in Hackney, east London – and its three sister establishments around the UK – accept Bitcoin. The digital currency is finally breaking into the mainstream. No longer is Bitcoin the preference of geeks and libertarians. After four years in circulation, it is now accepted in several bars, cafés and shops. You can use it to buy merchandise on social news site Reddit and pay WordPress to host your website or blog with it. So how does it work? Simply, digital currencies behave like cash. Payments are anonymous and you won’t pay transaction fees, because funds are transferred over a peer-to-peer hosted network. Your “money” can’t be lost, stolen or frozen. And there’s little risk of identity theft. Bitcoin is a virtual currency that is independent of any government or bank and transferred over the internet. Users have an online wallet (in the form of an app on their phone or computer) that holds their funds. When they pay in Bitcoins, these funds enter the recipient’s wallet about 10 minutes later. The payment process is simple. In the Pembury Tavern, for example, staff bring up a QR code on the till, which the payee can take a picture of through the Bitcoin app and use to confirm a payment. It sounds too good to be true. But despite boasting a growing fanbase – including internet entrepreneurs the Winklevoss twins, who claim to own 1 per cent of all Bitcoin – it is uncertain whether this early popularity will translate into global dominance. First, along with other alternative currencies, it is not legal tender. But the features that have made Bitcoin successful could also hinder it. Bitcoin was created in 2009 by an unknown hacker, or group of anonymous hackers, with the pseudonym Satoshi Nakamoto. Nakamoto published an online paper about the currency, launched it, then disappeared. So there is no central body responsible for its management. Today, Bitcoin is operated collectively by the people who exchange it, run the software and produce it. Many see this approach as positive. Yet such unaccountability may make governments and regulators nervous about giving it the status of legal tender. Indeed, success turned sour in April 2013, when the value of a Bitcoin peaked at $266 (£170) before plunging to $105 (£68) the following day. Such activity is bad news if you’re a vendor who accepts the currency and must keep changing prices. Dips can also trigger panic selling. Bitcoin is currently buoyant at $106 (£70), but these fluctuations can strike at any time – and they don’t just stem from market forces. In 2011, Mt Gox, the largest Bitcoin exchange (where you can buy or sell the currency), was hacked. This put the website offline, cutting Bitcoin’s value to $0.01 before the system recovered. Another reason value has swung so sharply is that Bitcoin is not determined by any tangible commodity. It is the commodity, drawing its value from demand. Its minting (or “mining”) process comes into play, too. Bitcoin is created on a network of servers, where powerful computers crunch complex mathematical problems. New coins are sent into the market (a bit like the Bank of England adding money to the economy). When someone pays another user, the transaction is recorded and secured by these Bitcoin miners. They track the history of the currency, creating a record. But, despite this, it has no material value, leaving it vulnerable to abandonment if enthusiasm drops off. So Bitcoin isn’t perfect. But there are hundreds of alternatives out there. Ripple is one. Like Bitcoin, it exists only in the digital space and is traded between those with Ripple wallets. But it isn’t produced through mining. Instead, its creator (Silicon Valley company OpenCoin) has made 100 billion Ripples to distribute slowly into the market. So while more Bitcoins will continue to enter the system as they’re mined, Ripple is already at its limit. OpenCoin claims that this approach will create a level playing field, whereas Bitcoin mining requires significant computer processing and is in the hands of the few. Ripple transactions are kept on a digital global ledger. The idea is that, by keeping it centralised, the currency can be better managed and more stable. The value of a Ripple has fluctuated little between £60 and £70 over the past month. But there have been harsh criticisms. It has been alleged that OpenCoin maintains the majority of Ripples itself, so if the currency succeeds, its founders stand to become wealthy. And its software is not open source. Unlike Bitcoin, it can’t be improved by anyone outside. Another option is Litecoin. Its transactions are four times faster (little more than two minutes as opposed to 10), it has four times more “coins” in circulation and can be created using desktop computers. Theoretically, this makes Litecoin better for small, fast payments, where Bitcoin is best for large ones. But as it has become more popular, Bitcoin is being traded faster and in smaller chunks. This has caused problems. On March 1, 2013, the record of every Bitcoin transaction was effectively duplicated. Under the stress of too many bitty transactions, a bug split the system in half. This meant two different versions of the Bitcoin “record” were in operation. Litecoin supporters say it would not happen with their more flexible option. These examples represent just a fraction of the digital currencies out there. In 2011, Ven was the first to be listed on Thomson Reuters. It is used in a social network, allowing Hub Culture users to buy, share and trade. This may seem like Facebook credits or Amazon Coins. But Ven’s value is determined by commodities such as precious metals, other currencies and carbon credits – in theory, making it relatively stable and green. PPCoin, meanwhile, offers superior security, while Freicoin features digital depreciation, encouraging spending, not stockpiling. Whether any of these can topple Bitcoin, or make a serious bid for the mass market, remains to be seen. Digital currencies face serious obstacles: security and user-growth aside, there are vast technical and logistical challenges. But the biggest hurdle may be governments and regulators who could attempt to control or profit from digital currencies. The revolution is coming. Who knows how we’ll pay? More from the technology trend series How future smartphones may bend us to their will >>
